SIMPLE: lordship
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lordship
<hw>Lord"ship</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
state or condition of being a lord; hence (with <xex>his</xex> or
<xex>your</xex>), a title applied to a lord (except an archbishop or
duke, who is called <xex>Grace</xex>) or a judge (in Great Britain),
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Seigniory; domain; the territory over which a lord
holds jurisdiction; a manor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What lands and <qex>lordships</qex> for their owner know⟦br⟧
My quondam barber.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Dominion; power; authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They which are accounted to rule over the Gentiles exercise
<qex>lordship</qex> over them.</q> <rj><qau>Mark x. 42.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lore</ent>⟦br⟧
